[The identification of "bovine respiratory disease (BRD)" as the main cause of losses during long-range voyage of cattle exported from Australia is not surprising. BRD is a multifactorial disease, caused by various infectious (bacterial and viral) pathogens combined with stress-related environmental factors. Transportation is the most universally accepted non-infectious risk factor for BRD and led to the long-known layman's term "shipping fever." While economically significant and animal-welfare related, BRD is not an emerging nor an infectious disease.

_Bos taurus_ and _Bos indicus_ breeds are 2 closely related cattle subspecies: _Bos taurus_ breeds are dairy, beef and dual-purpose cattle, mostly of European origin; many of them adapted to cooler climates. _Bos indicus_ are characterised by a fatty hump on their shoulders, drooping ears and a large dewlap; they are well adapted to high temperatures, mainly farmed in tropical countries, often cross-bred with _Bos taurus_ cattle.

According to the data available in West Australia's Department of Agriculture and Food website at http://tinyurl.com/qhw7tev, a total of 195 000 live cattle and 1.72 million live sheep were exported from Western Australia in 2012-13. The major export markets were Israel, Indonesia, Turkey, Malaysia and China. The Australian Government's Exporter Supply Chain Assurance System (ESCAS) has been introduced to ensure all livestock exported for slaughter are handled to internationally agreed (OIE) animal welfare standards and are able to be traced through the supply chain.

Further reading:
